Matter Physics</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>journal-subject-collection</meta-name><meta-value>Chemistry and Materials Science</meta-value></custom-meta><custom-meta><meta-name>open-access</meta-name><meta-value>false</meta-value></custom-meta></custom-meta-group></article-meta></front><body><p id="Par1">In the end, life comes down to electrochemical gradients. But we haven't yet found very effective ways of making what works for the cell work for society: harnessing the energy released by the equalization of solute concentrations. The power that could be tapped from the entropy of mixing of saline and fresh water, as rivers reach the sea, might seem tiny locally, but like everything else associated with the oceans, becomes vast on the global scale: of the order of a few terawatts, which would provide a significant fraction of current world energy demand. Highlighting this overlooked energy source in 1954, the engineer R. E. Pattle estimated that the energy released in a river estuary is equivalent to that available if the river were plunging over a 680-foot waterfall<sup><xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR1">1</xref></sup>.</p><p id="Par2">Of course, energy production from salinity gradients suffers the curse of all renewables: global sums sound appealing, but the energy is so dispersed that capturing even a small part of it is immensely challenging, technologically and economically. That hasn't prevented attempts since Pattle first proposed his 'hydroelectric pile'. Most notably, in the 1970s Sidney Loeb imagined harnessing the pressure generated as fresh water is drawn through a salt-obstructing membrane — a method called pressure-retarded osmosis, now being developed by the Norwegian-based renewable energy company Statkraft, which aims to have a commercial generator by 2015.</p><p id="Par3">There are several other proposed membrane-based technologies, but all depend on the cost and lifetime of the membranes themselves. A rather different approach was recently proposed by Brogioli<sup><xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR2">2</xref></sup>: a capacitor containing electrical double layers in salt-saturated films of activated carbon on the charged electrodes. As fresh water flushes out the salt, the consequent charge separation raises the voltage, allowing electricity to be tapped in a cyclical process.</p><p id="Par4">Now La Mantia <italic>et al</italic>. have described a related membrane-less 'saltwater battery' in which the salt ions are stored within the crystal structure of the electrodes themselves<sup><xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR3">3</xref></sup>. In the charging step, the intercalated ions (Na<sup>+</sup> and Cl<sup>−</sup>) are drawn out into dilute solution ('fresh water') between the electrodes. Changing the electrolyte for sea water raises the potential difference between them, and the battery is discharged as the ions are re-intercalated.</p><p id="Par5">The researchers used the sodium-intercalating material Na<sub>2</sub>Mn<sub>5</sub>O<sub>10</sub> as the cationic electrode, in the form of nanorods to increase the surface area. For this prototype, the anionic electrode was silver, which captures chloride reversibly to form AgCl, although for obvious reasons this would not be the ideal material for a commercial device. The power density (power per electrode area) for this device is 10.5 μW cm<sup>−2</sup>, corresponding to an energy extraction efficiency of around 74% — a figure that remains stable for at least 100 cycles. The battery can also be discharged by using solar heat to distill the water, offering solar-to-electrical energy conversion. A power plant that processes 40 m3 of river water per second could, based on these figures, generate up to 100 MW. Now needed, then, is a good, cheap and robust chloride intercalator.</p></body><back><ref-list id="Bib1"><title>References</title><ref-list><ref id="CR1"><label>1</label><mixed-citation publication-type="journal"><person-group person-group-type="author